There are many methods for sub-Doppler laser cooling of atoms to low temperatures. Among these, gray molasses is particularly efficient for atoms with poorly-resolved hyperfine structure, such as the isotopes of potassium and lithium. It combines the effects of Sisyphus cooling with a velocity-selective dark state, which prevents scattering of light by already-cold atoms.
Gray molasses relies on the presence of bright states, in which the atom interacts with the laser light, and dark states, which can be created either by using circularly polarized light on an 
  
    
      
