   transition or EIT-like coherent dark states. A spatially varying light shift of the bright states allows moving atoms to undergo a Sisyphus-like cooling effect. From here, atoms can be optically pumped to dark states. The coupling between the dark and bright states is engineered so that the coldest atoms are trapped in dark states but hot atoms return to the Sisyphus cooling cycle.
Historically, gray molasses was introduced with atomic species such as rubidium and cesium on the D2 line, but has more recently been used to enable efficient cooling of potassium and lithium using the D1 line. Avoiding the need of a separate laser system, D2-line gray molasses cooling has also been demonstrated in 40K.
